<p>noSol = $noSol</p> -->
<!--testing-->


<p>Find the solution to the system of equations:</p>
  <md>
    <mrow>$lhs1 \amp= $m</mrow>
    <mrow>$lhs2 \amp= $n</mrow>
  </md>


<!--*********************************************
            Graphing Tool
**********************************************-->

<aside><title>Graphing tool</title>
<sideBySide margins="5%" widths="30% 70%">
<div>
  <p>Enter the given equation of the first line:</p> 
  <p><mathInput name="graphEq1"/></p>

  <p>Enter the given equation of the second line:</p> 
  <p><mathInput name="graphEq2"/></p>


</div>

  
<graph name="g1">
  <point name="ip" coords="($graphX, $graphY)" fixed styleNumber="5">
    <label>$ip.coords</label>
  </point>
  <line name="line1" equation="$graphEq1" fixed/>
  <line name="line2" equation="$graphEq2" fixed styleNumber="2"/>
</graph>
  
  
</sideBySide>

  <p>Please answer the multiple-choice portion of the question before checking a proposed intersection point:</p>
  <p><m>(x,y) =  </m></p>
  <p><m>\bigg(</m> <mathInput name="graphX" bindValueTo="$userX" disabled="$otherSolutions.selectedIndices != 1"/> , <mathInput name="graphY" bindValueTo="$userY" disabled="$otherSolutions.selectedIndices != 1"/><m> \bigg)</m></p>

</aside>  

<!--*********************************************
            User-input of answers
**********************************************-->


<p>First, how many solutions are there for this system?</p>
  <choiceInput name="otherSolutions">
    <choice name="oneSolChoice">There is <alert>one solution</alert>; the point shown below.</choice>
    <choice name="infSolChoice">There are <alert>infinitely many solutions</alert> - the lines coincide.</choice>
    <choice name="noSolChoice">There are <alert>no solutions</alert> - the lines are separate but parallel.</choice>
  </choiceInput>

<p><m>(x, y) = \bigg(</m> <mathInput name="userX" disabled="$otherSolutions.selectedIndices != 1"/><m>,</m>
  <mathInput name="userY" disabled="$otherSolutions.selectedIndices != 1"/><m> \bigg)</m></p>
  
  <answer name="ans3">
    <award name="allCorrect">
      <when>$userX{isResponse} = $x and $userY{isResponse} = $y</when>
    </award>
    <award name="infAward">
      <when>$otherSolutions.selectedIndices = 2 and $infSol = true</when>
    </award>
    <award name="noSolAward">
      <when>$otherSolutions.selectedIndices = 3 and $noSol = true</when>
    </award>
    <award name="xIncorrect" credit="0.5">
      <when>$userX{isResponse} != $x and $userY{isResponse} = $y</when>
    </award>

    <award name="yIncorrect" credit="0.5">
      <when>$userX{isResponse} = $x and $userY{isResponse} != $y</when>
    </award>
    <award name="reverseXY" credit="0">
      <when>$userX{isResponse} = $y and $userY{isResponse} = $x</when>
    </award>
  </answer>

<p>Note, if a single solution exists, your values for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> should be in the form of an exact fraction or an integer, not a decimal approximation.</p>
<!--*********************************************
            Feedbacks
**********************************************-->
<setup>
  <select name="correctFeedback" type="text">
    <option>Awesome!</option>
    <option>Great job!</option>
    <option>Fantastic!</option>
    <option>Nice work!</option>
    <option>Amazing!</option>
    <option>Excellent!</option>
    <option>Right on!</option>
    <option>Perfect!</option>
  </select>
</setup>
  <feedback condition="$allCorrect">$correctFeedback</feedback>
  <feedback condition="$xIncorrect"><p>Your <m>x</m>-coordinate is incorrect.</p></feedback>
  <feedback condition="$yIncorrect"><p>Your <m>y</m>-coordinate is incorrect.</p></feedback>
  <feedback condition="$reverseXY"><p>Your <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>-coordinates are in the wrong spot. The ordered pair should be written as <m>(x,y)</m>.</p></feedback>
  <feedback condition="$ans3.numSubmissions > 2 and $ans3.creditAchieved != 1">
  <p>In this problem, we are given a system of two linear equations and are asked to find the solution. Graphically, this can be represented by two lines. The solution, if it exists, is their point of intersection.</p>
<p>To solve this problem algebraically, one can use several different techniques. Two of these methods are:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Substitution</li>
    <li>Elimination</li>
  </ul>
  
<p>You might find it easiest to use the method of elimination, if: when the two equations are added together, one variable immediately drops out.</p>
  </feedback>

  

<!--*********************************************
            Hint
**********************************************-->

<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
<solution>
<conditionalContent>
  <case condition="$infSol = true">There are infinitely many solutions.</case>
  <case condition="$noSol = true">There are no solutions.</case>
  <case condition="$infSol = false and $noSol = false">
    Use the method of substitution, or the method of elimination to obtain <m>(x,y) = ($x, $y)</m>
  </case>
</conditionalContent>
</solution>
</problem>

